"""
MKT Christ — Mark all 16 chapters
Output: data/commentary/mkt-christ/mark.json

Mark\'s Christology is Son of God (1:1) framed by the baptism (1:11) and
the centurion (15:39). The Messianic Secret creates a pattern:
Jesus\'s identity is progressively revealed through suffering, not power.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: the beginning of the gospel of Jesus Christ, Son of God. Mark\'s opening declaration is the entire Gospel in one sentence: the subject of all that follows is Jesus (personal name, human historical identity), Christ (the Messiah, the anointed one of Israel\'s hope), and Son of God (the divine identity that gives the Messiah infinite worth). The gospel (euangelion) is not a teaching but a person — the announcement that this person has come, has acted, has died, has risen. Everything in Mark\'s 16 chapters is the unpacking of this opening declaration.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: you are my beloved Son; with you I am well pleased. The Father\'s declaration at the baptism identifies Jesus publicly as the royal Son (Ps 2:7) and the Servant-figure (Isa 42:1) simultaneously. Mark\'s Christology holds these two together without harmonizing them: the royal Son is the Suffering Servant; the one destined for universal dominion is the one who will give his life as a ransom for many. Every subsequent event in Mark unfolds the content of this dual identity — the exorcisms and healings demonstrate the Son\'s authority; the cross demonstrates the Servant\'s self-giving.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: the kingdom of God has come near — repent and believe in the good news. Christ is not merely the herald of the kingdom but its embodiment: wherever Jesus is, the kingdom is present. His exorcisms are kingdom-conflict (plundering the strong man\'s house, 3:27); his healings are the kingdom\'s compassion reversing the curse; his teaching is the kingdom\'s wisdom clarifying God\'s intention. The announcement that the time is fulfilled names Jesus\'s arrival as the fulfillment of the Danielic kairos — the appointed eschatological moment has come in his person.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins. The Christological claim here is the most audacious of the Galilean ministry: Jesus exercises the divine prerogative of forgiveness not as a priestly representative applying a mechanism but in his own name, on his own authority, on earth. The Danielic Son of Man who received universal authority from the Ancient of Days is present in Capernaum, forgiving a paralytic, demonstrating that the eschatological reign has broken into the present through his person. The healing that follows makes the invisible forgiveness visible — the one who can do the harder thing (forgive) has demonstrated it by doing the visible thing (heal).</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: no one can enter a strong man\'s house and plunder his goods unless he first binds the strong man. The exorcisms are not individual humanitarian interventions but the systematic dismantling of the enemy\'s empire. Christ enters the strong man\'s house (the present age under demonic dominion) as the stronger one (the divine Son, anointed by the Spirit), binds the strong man (defeats Satan through the cross/resurrection), and plunders his goods (liberates those enslaved to demonic power). Every exorcism is an installment of this larger liberation — the kingdom\'s invasion of occupied territory.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: he awoke and rebuked the wind and said to the sea, Peace! Be still. The calming of the storm is the exercise of the divine sovereignty over the waters that the OT declares belongs to YHWH alone (Ps 107:29, Job 9:8). Jesus exercises this sovereignty in his own person, not by prayer or petition to God, but by command: his word silences the storm. The disciples\' terrified question (who is this that even the wind and sea obey him?) is the question that Ps 107 answers — YHWH, who stills the storm. Mark presents Jesus as the one doing what the Psalm says only YHWH does.</p>'
  },
  "5": {
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: Talitha koum — little girl, I say to you, arise. The resurrection of Jairus\'s daughter is the first explicit raising-from-death in Mark, performed with a simple Aramaic command. The contrast with later resurrection narratives (the elaborate prayer of Elijah in 1 Kgs 17:21, the stretching of Elisha over the boy in 2 Kgs 4:34-35) is stark: Jesus does not pray, does not invoke God, does not perform a ritual — he speaks to the dead girl as to a sleeping child. The command-authority over death revealed here is the authority that will be exercised in his own resurrection and in the final resurrection.</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: Peter answered him, You are the Christ. The Petrine confession at Caesarea Philippi is the structural center of Mark\'s Gospel. The immediate sequence that follows is theologically decisive: the Messianic Secret (silence commanded), the passion prediction (the Christ will suffer and die), and the call to cross-bearing. Mark\'s Christological argument is that the Messiah is only correctly understood as the Suffering Servant — to confess the Christ without the cross is to confess a misunderstood Christ. Peter\'s rebuke (v.32) and Jesus\'s sharp response (get behind me, Satan) demonstrate that Messiahship divorced from suffering is a Satanic distortion, not a divine truth.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: if anyone wishes to come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me. The cross is not a Markan metaphor for general difficulty but a specific path: the path Christ himself walked. Discipleship in Mark is defined by cross-bearing — sharing the master\'s path of self-denial, rejection, suffering, and death in the confidence of resurrection. The cross-bearing community is the community shaped by the Christology: the Son of God who died reveals what it means to follow the Son of God who died. Mark\'s suffering community (addressed in the Roman persecution context) is being told that their cross-bearing is not a contradiction of the gospel but its confirmation.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "45": '<p>A direct revelation: the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve and to give his life as a ransom for many. Mark\'s version of the ransom saying is the definitive self-interpretation of the cross in this Gospel. The movement is from the Danielic Son of Man (who receives universal service, Dan 7:14) to the Isaianic Servant (who gives his life for the many, Isa 53:12) — Jesus holds both identities and describes their synthesis: the one who deserves all service gives himself for others\' ransom. The cross is not the defeat of the Son of Man but the specific form in which the Son of Man\'s authority is exercised.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: is it not written, My house shall be called a house of prayer for all the nations? Jesus\'s temple action is a Christological claim: he acts with the authority of the temple\'s owner and designer (the divine author of Isa 56:7), overturning what has violated its purpose and restoring its universal-prayer function. The cursing of the fig tree (11:12-14) and the withering confirmed (11:20-21) frame the temple action, suggesting that the temple institution itself is under the same judgment as the fruitless tree. Christ is both fulfilling the temple\'s purpose and announcing its coming replacement by the community gathered around himself.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: take; this is my body. The Last Supper words are the most concentrated Christological claim in Mark: Jesus identifies the bread with his body and the cup with the blood of the covenant poured out for many. He interprets his own impending death through the Passover and Sinai covenant frameworks — his body is the Passover lamb whose blood protects from judgment, and his blood is the covenant blood of Sinai that ratifies the relationship between God and people. The Lord\'s Supper instituted here is the permanent memorial of the one historical event on which the new covenant community is founded.</p>',
    "62": '<p>A direct revelation: I am; and you will see the Son of Man seated at the right hand of Power and coming with the clouds of heaven. Jesus\'s response before the high priest is the most explicit Christological self-disclosure in Mark. At the moment of maximum vulnerability (arrested, tried, abandoned), Jesus speaks the most comprehensive claim: he is the I AM (the divine self-identification), the enthroned Son of Man at God\'s right hand (Ps 110:1), and the coming one with divine glory (Dan 7:13). The humiliation does not diminish the claim; it is the form in which the claim reaches its fullest expression — the Son of God who dies is the Son of God who reigns.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: my God, my God, why have you forsaken me? The cry of dereliction is a Christological statement about substitutionary atonement: the Son of God genuinely experiences God-forsakenness as the penalty of sin he bears for others. This is not theatrical or only apparent — the spiritual weight of bearing what separates humanity from God is real, and Jesus bears it in his own person. The darkness (v.33), the cry, and the death together constitute the atonement: at Golgotha, God in Christ is in the place of the God-forsaken, absorbing the wrath that sin deserves, so that those who trust him never need to experience that forsakenness themselves.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: truly this man was Son of God. The centurion\'s confession at the cross is Mark\'s Christological climax. The Gospel that opened with the declaration Jesus Christ, Son of God (1:1) and that the demons recognized throughout (1:24, 3:11, 5:7) now receives its human confession — from a Roman soldier, not a Jewish disciple, at the moment of death, not of triumph. Mark argues that the cross is not the refutation of the divine sonship but its revelation: it is precisely the manner of his death (v.39 — how he died) that leads the centurion to the confession. The Son of God is most clearly seen at the cross.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: he has been raised; he is not here. The resurrection announcement by the young man (angel) in the empty tomb is the counterpart to the Father\'s declaration at the baptism: the one identified as the beloved Son (1:11) is the one raised from the dead (16:6). Mark does not narrate resurrection appearances (in the original ending) but declares the resurrection and points forward to Galilee — the community is to follow the risen Lord as they followed the living Lord through Mark\'s Gospel. The resurrection vindicates everything Jesus claimed and fulfills every passion prediction; it is the Father\'s endorsement of the Son\'s entire Messianic-Servant mission.'
  }
}

# Gap-fill for ch 3 (v27 already in DATA — skipped by merge_comm)
FILL_CH3 = {
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The synagogue healing of the man with the withered hand opens the Sabbath controversy that will lead directly to the death plot (v.6). The withered hand recalls Zechariah 11:17 (the arm of the worthless shepherd shall wither) — Jesus reverses the curse, enacting the restoration promised to Israel. Entering the synagogue again (cf. 1:21) shows Jesus operating within covenant worship space, claiming authority to reinterpret its traditions.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The hostile surveillance of the religious authorities anticipates the trial scenes where the same leaders seek evidence against him (14:1, 14:55-59). The pattern of watch-accuse-condemn is established here in miniature before it is enacted at full scale in the passion.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Stand up in front of everyone&#8221; — the command to stand (<em>egeire</em>, cognate of the resurrection verb) is not accidental in Mark; healing commands frequently use rising language that anticipates resurrection. The public setting is deliberate: Jesus refuses private accommodation of the authorities&#8217; sensitivities and makes the healing a theological demonstration.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;Which is lawful on the Sabbath — to do good or to do evil, to save life or to kill?&#8221; — the question is a Christological claim: Jesus asserts the authority to rule on what the Sabbath requires. The contrast &#8220;save life / kill&#8221; is charged with dramatic irony — the authorities who refuse to save life on the Sabbath are at this very moment plotting to kill (v.6). Jesus is the one who saves life; they choose to take it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Grief and anger at their hardness of heart — &#8220;hardness of heart&#8221; (<em>pōrōsis tēs kardias</em>) is Exodus/prophetic language for Pharaoh and Israel&#8217;s recurrent failure (Isa 6:10, Ezek 3:7). The healed hand and the hardened hearts stand in deliberate contrast: Jesus opens what is shut, while opponents shut themselves against the kingdom&#8217;s coming.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Pharisees and Herodians conspire to kill Jesus — the first formal death plot in Mark, placed immediately after the Sabbath controversy. The improbable alliance between religious conservatives and political pragmatists anticipates the Pilate-chief priest collaboration in the passion. Opposition to Jesus crosses ideological lines; the cross will unite all such opponents in their shared rejection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jesus withdraws to the sea with his disciples — each withdrawal in Mark signals a reorientation from confrontation to ministry. The sea is liminal space where Jesus teaches, crosses, and demonstrates divine power. The great crowd following foreshadows the eschatological gathering of peoples before the Son of Man.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The crowd comes from Galilee, Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, Transjordan, Tyre, and Sidon — a geography spanning the entire land and beyond. The scope signals Isaiah 49:6 (the servant as light to the nations); the one born in Bethlehem obscurity draws the nations before the cross draws all people to him (John 12:32).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A small boat as protection against the crowd — the boat becomes a recurring element in Markan Christology (4:1, 4:36-41, 6:32, 6:47-51). From the boat Jesus teaches; in the boat his disciples are tested; on the water Jesus walks. The boat is the space where proximity to Jesus is both intensified and revealing.</p>",
    "10": "<p>All who had diseases pressed to touch him — the urgency of physical contact with Jesus as the locus of divine healing power anticipates the woman with the hemorrhage (5:27-28). Mark&#8217;s Christology includes the enfleshed body of Jesus as the site of grace — not merely his words but his physical presence mediates the kingdom&#8217;s power.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Unclean spirits fall down and cry &#8220;You are the Son of God&#8221; — the pattern first established in 1:24. The demonic realm recognizes Jesus&#8217;s transcendent identity before any human disciple does. &#8220;Son of God&#8221; carries messianic weight (Ps 2:7, 2 Sam 7:14) plus divine sonship that the Gospel will develop toward the centurion&#8217;s confession (15:39). The spirits prostrate themselves — worship language — before the one who will destroy their domain.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Strict orders not to tell who he was — the Messianic Secret operates because Jesus&#8217;s identity, if proclaimed by demonic spirits, would be catastrophically misread. A king revealed by demons might be understood as a supernatural political liberator; the true disclosure of the Son of God requires the cross and resurrection as its interpretive framework.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Jesus went up on a mountainside and called to him those he wanted&#8221; — the mountain recalls Sinai as the site of covenant formation. The sovereign initiative — &#8220;those he wanted&#8221; — mirrors divine election (cf. John 15:16). The Twelve are called, not recruited; their election is entirely Christ&#8217;s initiative.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;He appointed twelve&#8221; — the number 12 is a symbolic claim: Jesus appoints twelve as the nucleus of a reconstituted covenant people organized around himself rather than around Torah, Temple, or ethnic descent. The two-part purpose — &#8220;that they might be with him&#8221; and &#8220;that he might send them out&#8221; — establishes the pattern of all Christian discipleship: first intimacy with Jesus, then mission flowing from it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Authority to drive out demons — the Twelve share in Jesus&#8217;s own authority over the powers; this is delegated participation in Jesus&#8217;s messianic warfare. The authority given here will be exercised in 6:7-13 and will fail in 9:18, prompting teaching on prayer. Authority over demons is inseparable from proximity to Jesus.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Simon, to whom he gave the name Peter — name-giving in the OT is a prerogative of God and kings (Gen 17:5, Isa 62:2); Jesus exercises royal authority by renaming Simon, signaling that Peter&#8217;s identity and destiny are determined by his relationship to Jesus. The renamed Peter will first confess Jesus as Messiah (8:29) and first deny him (14:66-72).</p>",
    "17": "<p>James and John called Boanerges — &#8220;Sons of Thunder&#8221; — the surname is unique to Mark; it reflects their temperament (10:35-37, Luke 9:54) and the fierce quality the Spirit will transform into apostolic boldness. Jesus names them by character and sovereign purpose, calling even flawed disciples.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The remaining eight: Andrew, Philip and Bartholomew, Matthew and Thomas, James son of Alphaeus and Thaddaeus, Simon the Zealot — a political revolutionary and a tax collector (Matthew) called into the same community speaks to the kingdom&#8217;s power to overcome social and political divisions that otherwise preclude fellowship.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Judas Iscariot, &#8220;who betrayed him&#8221; — the shadow of the passion falls immediately on the election list. Mark does not explain why Jesus chose his betrayer; the theological weight falls on the fact that Jesus knew and chose anyway, walking toward the cross with open eyes. Judas participates — however unwillingly — in the divine plan.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;Such a large crowd gathered that he and his disciples were not even able to eat&#8221; — the consuming pressure of the crowd anticipates the total self-giving that culminates at the Last Supper, where Jesus distributes himself as bread. The inability to eat here stands in contrast with the later feeding miracles; Jesus will feed multitudes while himself consumed by others&#8217; need.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;When his family heard about this, they went to take charge of him, for they said, &#8216;He is out of his mind&#8217;&#8221; — the family&#8217;s disbelief creates the frame for the true-family redefinition in vv.31-35. &#8220;Out of his mind&#8221; (<em>existēmi</em>) parallels the scribes&#8217; accusation of demonic possession. Both groups reduce the inexplicable to a pathology; both are answered by the parable of the strong man.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Jerusalem scribes: &#8220;He is possessed by Beelzebul! By the prince of demons he is driving out demons&#8221; — the accusation inverts reality: the one who defeats demons is labeled demonic. This is the functional accusation behind the blasphemy charge at the trial (14:64) — they attribute the Spirit&#8217;s work through Jesus to Satan.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;How can Satan drive out Satan?&#8221; — the parabolic response is logical before it is theological: a divided kingdom falls. The deeper point is that Jesus&#8217;s exorcisms are not a civil war within the demonic realm but a frontal assault on it by a stronger power. The parables of the kingdom in ch 4 will develop this logic of the stronger one&#8217;s victory.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;If a kingdom is divided against itself, that kingdom cannot stand&#8221; — the political analogy establishes the reductio ad absurdum of the scribes&#8217; position. The kingdom Jesus brings is undivided because it centers on one king whose rule is eternal; the kingdom that will fall is Satan&#8217;s, already being dismantled by the exorcisms.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;If a house is divided against itself, that house cannot stand&#8221; — the shift from &#8220;kingdom&#8221; to &#8220;house&#8221; (<em>oikos</em>) anticipates the strong man&#8217;s house (<em>oikia</em>) in v.27 and plays on the name Beelzebul (&#8220;lord of the house&#8221;). Jesus is entering Beelzebul&#8217;s house — the domain of demonic oppression — to plunder it.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;If Satan opposes himself and is divided, he cannot stand; his end has come&#8221; — the conditional refutation concludes with &#8220;his end has come,&#8221; an eschatological declaration. The exorcisms are the early stages of a defeat completed at the cross and resurrection (cf. John 12:31, Col 2:15).</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;Truly I tell you, people can be forgiven all their sins and every slander they utter&#8221; — the unforgivable-sin pericope opens with the widest possible declaration of available forgiveness. The breadth is Christological: Jesus speaks as the one through whom this forgiveness is mediated; the cross has not yet been described, but the announcement points forward to it.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;But whoever blasphemes against the Holy Spirit will never be forgiven; they are guilty of an eternal sin&#8221; — the scribes&#8217; charge attributes the Spirit&#8217;s work through Jesus to Satan. The sin is &#8220;eternal&#8221; (<em>aiōnion</em>) not because God&#8217;s capacity to forgive is limited but because those who commit it have placed themselves permanently outside the repentance that leads to forgiveness. They have called the healer a disease.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;He said this because they were saying, &#8216;He has an impure spirit&#8217;&#8221; — Mark&#8217;s explanatory note confirms the occasion. The Spirit who anointed Jesus at his baptism (1:10) is the same Spirit through whom he heals; to call that Spirit impure is to reject the mechanism of all divine forgiveness.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;Then Jesus&#8217; mother and brothers arrived&#8221; — the structural hinge of the chapter. Standing outside — the physical positioning of family &#8220;outside&#8221; vs. disciples &#8220;around him inside&#8221; (v.34) — enacts the redefinition of inside and outside that Jesus is about to pronounce. Physical family proximity is not spiritual proximity.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;Your mother and brothers are outside looking for you&#8221; — the announcement from the crowd poses the test: will Jesus prioritize biological kinship over the new covenant community? The contrast &#8220;outside / inside&#8221; is the same spatial-spiritual distinction found in 4:11 (the secret of the kingdom given to insiders, parables for those outside).</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;Who are my mother and my brothers?&#8221; — the rhetorical question does not deny his mother (who will appear at the cross, John 19:25-27) but relativizes all biological kinship in light of the eschatological family being formed around Jesus. The question is the Christological pivot: around whom is the new family organized?</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;Here are my mother and my brothers!&#8221; — looking at those seated in the circle, Jesus visually enacts the new covenant community. The circle around Jesus is the prototype of the church: gathered around the one who teaches, constituted by obedience to his word, defined by relationship to him.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;Whoever does God&#8217;s will is my brother and sister and mother&#8221; — God&#8217;s will (<em>thelēma tou theou</em>) is the criterion of belonging to Jesus&#8217;s family. This anticipates the Lord&#8217;s Prayer (&#8220;your will be done&#8221;) and Gethsemane (&#8220;not what I will, but what you will,&#8221; 14:36). Jesus is the one who does God&#8217;s will perfectly — the family consists of those who follow him in this.</p>"
  }
}

# Gap-fill for ch 4 (v39 already in DATA — skipped by merge_comm)
FILL_CH4 = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>Teaching from a boat on the lake — the boat becomes a pulpit, echoing the divine word that goes out over the waters (Gen 1:2, Ps 29). The crowd on the shore while Jesus teaches from the water enacts the separation and address that characterizes the prophets&#8217; ministry; Jesus speaks from liminal space appropriate to the one who crosses all boundaries.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;He taught them many things by parables&#8221; — the parabolic method is the form of speech appropriate to the hiddenness of the incarnation. The kingdom comes disguised in the ordinary (seed, lamp, tree), as the King comes disguised in flesh. Those who have eyes to see recognize the extraordinary within the ordinary.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Listen!&#8221; (<em>Akouete</em>) — the parable begins with the Shema imperative (Deut 6:4). Jesus&#8217;s summons to hear is the summons of Israel&#8217;s covenant God who demands the undivided attention of the whole person. The parable is not entertainment but a call to the kind of hearing that determines eschatological fate.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Seed on the path — eaten by birds before it can take root. The hardened path represents a heart closed by habitual resistance. The birds that devour the unprotected word will recur in v.32 (the mustard tree shelters birds) — the same creatures appear in both judgment and hospitality imagery.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Rocky ground with shallow soil — quick growth is a false sign; the absence of deep roots (depth of relationship with Jesus) means the plant cannot survive the heat of opposition. Superficial enthusiasm for Jesus is not saving faith.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;When the sun came up, the plants were scorched&#8221; — the sun that gives life to deep-rooted plants destroys the shallow. Suffering and the demands of discipleship reveal whether faith is rooted in Christ or in the benefits of his presence. The disciples&#8217; later failures (14:50, 14:66-72) will illustrate this soil.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Thorns choke the growing plant — the desires for other things (v.19) are structurally incompatible with the word taking hold. The gospel requires the whole person; it does not fit alongside competing ultimate concerns. This soil anticipates the rich young man (10:22) who goes away sad because his possessions hold him.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Good soil produces thirty, sixty, a hundred times what was sown — the yield is eschatological surplus, far beyond normal Palestinian harvests. The multiplication recalls the feeding miracles (6:30-44; 8:1-10) where Jesus multiplies loaves beyond calculation. The harvest points forward to the resurrection: from one grain dying, an incalculable life.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;Whoever has ears to hear, let them hear&#8221; — the parable closes with invitation and warning. It is an invitation because ears to hear are a gift that can be sought; it is a warning because not everyone who physically hears understands. Jesus as the Word made flesh (John 1:14) is himself the object of this hearing — to hear his word rightly is to receive him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Twelve and the wider circle ask about the parables when alone — proximity to Jesus is the decisive factor in understanding. The disciples do not understand automatically; they ask. The act of seeking Jesus for explanation is itself the model of discipleship: those who pursue Jesus receive illumination.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;The secret of the kingdom of God has been given to you&#8221; — <em>mystērion</em> is Paul&#8217;s later term for the hidden plan of God revealed in Christ (Eph 1:9, Col 1:27). Here Jesus identifies himself as the one in whom the kingdom&#8217;s secret is present; the secret is not information but a person. To be with Jesus is to have the mystery; to be without him is to remain outside however many parables one hears.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;So that they may be ever seeing but never perceiving&#8221; — Isaiah 6:9-10, the great hardening text, is quoted as the purpose of parabolic teaching. This is not predestination to damnation but a judgment that confirms the stance people have already taken: those who come to Jesus with open hearts see; those who approach with hostility are confirmed in their blindness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Don&#8217;t you understand this parable? How then will you understand any parable?&#8221; — Jesus challenges the disciples&#8217; comprehension; this is the first of Mark&#8217;s repeated misunderstanding scenes (6:52; 7:18; 8:17, 21; 9:32). Full understanding waits for the Spirit after the resurrection (John 16:13).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;The farmer sows the word&#8221; — the interpretive key. &#8220;The word&#8221; (<em>logos</em>) is Jesus&#8217;s proclamation (1:45; 2:2; 4:33); in John, &#8220;the Word&#8221; is Jesus himself (John 1:1). Jesus is simultaneously the sower, the seed (the word embodied), and the field in which all things grow. The parable is a self-portrait.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Seed on the path — Satan immediately takes the word. The cosmic adversary introduced in the wilderness temptation (1:12-13) is now named as the opponent of the word&#8217;s reception. Every proclamation of the gospel is contested; the soil that does not respond allows the adversary to remove what was sown.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Rocky-ground hearers — receive the word with joy but have no root; &#8220;when trouble or persecution comes because of the word, they quickly fall away.&#8221; The Greek <em>skandalizontai</em> (they stumble) is the same word used for Peter&#8217;s impending fall (14:27, 29). Joy at Jesus&#8217;s presence does not guarantee endurance through his suffering.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;Since they have no root, they last only a short time&#8221; — rootlessness is the fundamental diagnosis. Root imagery in the OT describes Israel&#8217;s establishment in covenant (Isa 27:6; Jer 17:8); to be rooted in Christ is to participate in the life he provides. These hearers have the surface but not the relationship.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Thorny-ground hearers — the word is sown but the worries of this life, the deceitfulness of wealth, and the desires for other things crowd in and choke it. The plurality of competing desires contrasts with the single-mindedness of the good-soil hearer (v.20). Undivided attention to the word requires willing dispossession — exactly what Jesus will call for in 10:21.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;The deceitfulness of wealth&#8221; — wealth is &#8220;deceitful&#8221; (<em>apatē</em>) because it promises the security and sufficiency that belong to God alone. The disciples who have left everything (1:18, 20; 2:14) have removed the thorns; the rich young man who will not (10:22) remains choked. The kingdom calls for a transfer of ultimate trust from possessions to the person of Jesus.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Good-soil hearers — &#8220;hear the word, accept it, and produce a crop.&#8221; The three-part description is the Christological response pattern: <em>hear</em> (receive the word addressed to you), <em>accept</em> (welcome it as authoritative), <em>produce</em> (the transformed life bears kingdom fruit — more disciples, more proclamation, the harvest multiplied).</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Do you bring in a lamp to put it under a bowl or a bed?&#8221; — the lamp is the revelation of the kingdom brought by Jesus; the Messianic Secret is temporary, not permanent. The light is hidden in the incarnation so that it may be revealed in the resurrection. What Jesus whispered in the days of his flesh will be proclaimed from the housetops.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;For whatever is hidden is meant to be disclosed, and whatever is concealed is meant to be brought out into the open&#8221; — the purpose of the hiddenness is its eventual disclosure. The resurrection is the great unveiling of all that was hidden in Jesus&#8217;s earthly ministry: his identity as Son of God, the meaning of his death, the nature of the kingdom.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;If anyone has ears to hear, let them hear&#8221; — the invitation of v.9 repeated, bracketing the lamp and measure sayings. The parable of the Sower, its interpretation, and these supplementary parables are all part of one teaching about how the word of the kingdom works. Hearing rightly is the through-line.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Consider carefully what you hear. With the measure you use, it will be measured to you&#8221; — attentiveness to Jesus&#8217;s teaching is not passive; it is the active posture of faith. The measure of attention given to the word determines what is received back. Those who apply themselves to the word receive an abundance; those who give it partial attention receive correspondingly less.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;Whoever has will be given more; whoever does not have, even what they have will be taken from them&#8221; — the paradoxical economy of the kingdom: spiritual understanding grows when exercised and withers when neglected. Proximity to Jesus is maintained by seeking; the disciples who pursue Jesus (v.10) are given more; those who do not pursue lose even what they received.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The seed growing secretly — unique to Mark, this parable addresses the hiddenness of the kingdom&#8217;s growth between the first and second coming of Christ. <em>Automate</em> (by itself, automatically) points to God&#8217;s sovereign action in history that does not depend on human understanding. Jesus&#8217;s death and resurrection will look like failure; the harvest (v.29) will come on God&#8217;s timetable.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;Night and day, whether he sleeps or gets up, the seed sprouts and grows&#8221; — the continuity of the seed&#8217;s growth regardless of the farmer&#8217;s waking state emphasizes divine agency. Between the resurrection and the parousia, the kingdom grows through the proclaimed word while the Church both labors and rests; the outcome does not depend on perpetual human vigilance but on the word&#8217;s inherent vitality.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;All by itself the soil produces grain — first the stalk, then the head, then the full kernel in the head&#8221; — the stages of growth are the stages of redemptive history: the ministry of Jesus (stalk), the apostolic mission (head forming), the full harvest at the end of the age (kernel). The process has an internal logic; the end is certain because the beginning has been planted by the sower.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;As soon as the grain is ripe, he puts the sickle to it, because the harvest has come&#8221; — the harvest image invokes Joel 3:13 (eschatological judgment and ingathering). Jesus is both the sower who plants the word and the lord of the harvest who will return to gather what has grown. The certainty of the harvest is the ground of confidence throughout the age of hiddenness.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;What shall we say the kingdom of God is like?&#8221; — Jesus&#8217;s self-questioning before the mustard seed parable signals that human language approaches the kingdom&#8217;s reality obliquely. The act of seeking the right parable models the proper intellectual posture before the mystery of God&#8217;s reign: continual, humble searching.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;It is like a mustard seed, which is the smallest of all seeds on earth&#8221; — the smallness is the point: the kingdom&#8217;s visible beginning in a single man from Nazareth, executed under Roman authority, is as unpromising as a mustard seed. The incarnation chooses weakness and obscurity; the cross looks like the smallest, most insignificant end. This is the way the kingdom comes.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;Yet when planted, it grows and becomes the largest of all garden plants&#8221; — the eschatological reversal. &#8220;The birds of the air perch in its branches&#8221; echoes Ezekiel 17:23 and Daniel 4:12, where a great tree sheltering birds represents an empire encompassing all peoples. Jesus&#8217;s kingdom surpasses all earthly empires by the humility of its origin and the universality of its hospitality.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;With many such parables Jesus spoke the word to them, as much as they could understand&#8221; — the parables are measured to the capacity of the hearers; Jesus does not overwhelm but gradually opens the mystery as disciples grow. The progressive disclosure model of the parables mirrors the progressive revelation of Scripture: the OT types contained what the NT proclamation unfolds.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;He did not say anything to them without using a parable. But when he was alone with his disciples, he explained everything&#8221; — the two-tier teaching maps onto the structure of revelation: the parables are the OT types and shadows; the private explanation to the disciples is the NT fulfillment. Jesus alone has the authority to explain the mysteries of the kingdom because he is both their content and their interpreter.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;Let us go over to the other side&#8221; — the crossing to the Gentile side of the Sea of Galilee initiates the kingdom&#8217;s expansion beyond Israel. The &#8220;other side&#8221; (<em>eis to peran</em>) is used six times in Mark for Gentile territory. Jesus actively crosses the ethnic and geographic boundary that defines Israel&#8217;s self-understanding; the kingdom is not bounded by Israel&#8217;s borders.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;They took him along, just as he was, in the boat&#8221; — the &#8220;just as he was&#8221; detail is unique to Mark and emphasizes the genuine humanity of Jesus: not a prepared or protected figure but the weary man who had been teaching all day. The incarnation means vulnerability; the one who will still the storm is truly exhausted before doing so.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A furious squall — <em>lailaps</em> (squall/whirlwind) is a technical term for a severe storm arising suddenly; the Sea of Galilee is prone to such storms. The Jonah parallel is structural: a man asleep in a storm-tossed boat, with terrified companions who wake him (Jonah 1:4-6). Jesus will still the storm where Jonah could not — and at the cross, unlike Jonah, he will give his life willingly rather than be sacrificed.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Jesus asleep in the stern — the cushion detail (unique to Mark) emphasizes the physical reality of his exhaustion. The disciples&#8217; desperate question — &#8220;Teacher, don&#8217;t you care if we drown?&#8221; — echoes Psalm 44:23 (&#8220;Rouse yourself! Why do you sleep, Lord?&#8221;) and invokes the covenant language of divine watchfulness from the one they have not yet identified as the Lord who neither slumbers nor sleeps (Ps 121:4).</p>",
    "40": "<p>&#8220;Why are you so afraid? Do you still have no faith?&#8221; — Jesus rebukes the disciples after stilling the storm. The rebuke is pedagogical: the disciples&#8217; fear and lack of faith are the exact failures that the resurrection will address. To have faith in Jesus as Lord of creation is the proper response to his presence; the disciples are not yet capable of this because they do not yet know who he is.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&#8220;Who is this? Even the wind and the waves obey him!&#8221; — the central Christological question of the Gospel. Psalm 89:9 (&#8220;You rule over the surging sea; when its waves mount up, you still them&#8221;) and Psalm 107:28-30 (God stills the storm) are the OT backdrop; Jesus exercises the authority Scripture attributes to YHWH alone. The answer to &#8220;Who is this?&#8221; is given finally by the centurion at the cross (15:39): Son of God.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH3)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH4)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
